{"title_page": "John Lafayette Camp", "text_new": "{{other people||John Camp (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = John Lafayette Camp\n| image        =\n| title        =  [[Texas Senate|Texas State Senator]]<br>[[Texas Senate, District 6|District&nbsp;6]]\n| term_start   = 1874\n| term_end     = 1876\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1828|2|20}}\n| birth_place  = [[Jefferson County, Alabama]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1891|7|16|1828|2|20}}\n| death_place  = [[San Antonio, Texas]]\n| restingplace = \n| party        = [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]\n| spouse       = Mary Ann ''Ward''\n| children     =\n| profession   = [[Lawyer]]\n| religion     =\n| allegiance   = {{flag|Confederate States|1861b}}\n| branch       = {{army|CSA}}\n| unit         = {{flagicon|Texas}} 10th Texas Cavalry\n| rank         = [[File:Confederate States of America Colonel.png|30px]] [[Colonel]]\n}}\n\n'''John Lafayette Camp''' (February 20, 1828 &ndash; July 16, 1891) was an [[Americans|American]] lawyer and planter from [[Texas]] who served in the Texas state Senate and as a district court judge.\n\nJohn was born in [[Jefferson County, Alabama]], the son of John and Elizabeth Camp. After graduating from the [[University of Tennessee at Knoxville|University of Tennessee]] in 1848 he moved to [[Gilmer, Texas|Gilmer]] in [[Upshur County, Texas]]. He started a plantation and was admitted to the bar. In 1851 he married Mary Ann Ward, the daughter of a local doctor. The couple would have five children, including [[John Lafayette Camp Jr.|John Lafayette, Jr]].\n\n==Civil war==\nCamp entered to [[American Civil War|Civil War]] by joining the [[Confederate States Army]]. He joined the [[14th Texas Cavalry Regiment]] and was elected Captain of his company. By the end of the war, he was Colonel of the 10th Texas Cavalry, and attached to the [[Confederate Army of Tennessee|Army of Tennessee]]. He was in actions at Cumberland Gap, [[Battle of Stones River|Murfreesboro]], and [[Battle of Chickamauga|Chickamauga]]. John was wounded and captured twice.\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1866, the first district in Texas elected Camp to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congress]]. However, in the struggle over seating of delegations connected with the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]], he was not allowed to take his seat. He remained active in [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] politics.\n\nCamp was elected to the Texas State Senate in 1874, and served from 1875 to 1878, when [[Richard B. Hubbard|Governor Hubbard]] appointed him a judge in State district court. He resigned as a judge in 1878 due to poor health.\n\n==Later life==\nCamp moved to [[Arizona]] in 1884, working as a registrar in the land office. But, when the drier climate failed to improve his health, he came back to Texas two years later. He settled in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], living in his later years with his son, [[John Lafayette Camp, Jr.]]. He died there in 1891 and is buried in the Dignowitty Cemetery.<ref name=\"Grave\" />\n\n[[Camp County, Texas]] was named for him after he introduced the Bill in the state Senate that created the county.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Handbook of Texas|id=fca29|name=John Lafayette Camp}}\n*{{Find a Grave|27761101}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Grave\">{{cite web |title=Col John Lafayette Camp |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/27761101/john-lafayette-camp |publisher=Find A Grave |accessdate=23 August 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-tx-sen}}\n{{s-bef | before= [[John Lane Henry]]}}\n{{s-ttl\n|  title= [[Texas Senate|Texas State Senator]]<br />from&nbsp;[[Texas Senate, District 6|District&nbsp;6]]\n|  years= 1874-1876}}\n{{s-aft | rows=1 | after=[[William Amos Wortham]] }}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Camp County, Texas}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Camp, John Lafayette}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:1891 deaths]]\n[[Category:Texas state senators]]\n[[Category:Texas lawyers]]\n[[Category:Texas state court judges]]\n[[Category:Texas Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Jefferson County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People from Cass County, Texas]]\n[[Category:People from Gilmer, Texas]]\n[[Category:People of Texas in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n[[Category:American planters]]\n[[Category:Confederate States Army officers]]\n[[Category:People from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Camp County, Texas]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||John Camp (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = John Lafayette Camp\n| image        =\n| title        =  [[Texas Senate|Texas State Senator]]<br>[[Texas Senate, District 6|District&nbsp;6]]\n| term_start   = 1874\n| term_end     = 1876\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1828|2|20}}\n| birth_place  = [[Jefferson County, Alabama]]\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1891|7|16|1828|2|20}}\n| death_place  = [[San Antonio, Texas]]\n| restingplace = \n| party        = [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]\n| spouse       = Mary Ann ''Ward''\n| children     =\n| profession   = [[Lawyer]]\n| religion     =\n| allegiance   = {{flag|Confederate States|1861b}}\n| branch       = {{army|CSA}}\n| unit         = {{flagicon|Texas}} 10th Texas Cavalry\n| rank         = [[File:Confederate States of America Colonel.png|30px]] [[Colonel]]\n}}\n\n'''John Lafayette Camp''' (February 20, 1828 &ndash; July 16, 1891) was an [[Americans|American]] lawyer and planter from [[Texas]] who served in the Texas state Senate and as a district court judge.\n\nJohn was born in [[Jefferson County, Alabama]], the son of John and Elizabeth Camp. After graduating from the [[University of Tennessee at Knoxville|University of Tennessee]] in 1848 he moved to [[Gilmer, Texas|Gilmer]] in [[Upshur County, Texas]]. He started a plantation and was admitted to the bar. In 1851 he married Mary Ann Ward, the daughter of a local doctor. The couple would have five children, including [[John Lafayette Camp Jr.|John Lafayette, Jr]].\n\n==Civil war==\nCamp entered to [[American Civil War|Civil War]] by joining the [[Confederate States Army]]. He joined the 14th Texas Cavalry and was elected Captain of his company. By the end of the war, he was Colonel of the 10th Texas Cavalry, and attached to the [[Confederate Army of Tennessee|Army of Tennessee]]. He was in actions at Cumberland Gap, [[Battle of Stones River|Murfreesboro]], and [[Battle of Chickamauga|Chickamauga]]. John was wounded and captured twice.\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1866, the first district in Texas elected Camp to the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congress]]. However, in the struggle over seating of delegations connected with the [[Reconstruction era of the United States|Reconstruction]], he was not allowed to take his seat. He remained active in [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]] politics.\n\nCamp was elected to the Texas State Senate in 1874, and served from 1875 to 1878, when [[Richard B. Hubbard|Governor Hubbard]] appointed him a judge in State district court. He resigned as a judge in 1878 due to poor health.\n\n==Later life==\nCamp moved to [[Arizona]] in 1884, working as a registrar in the land office. But, when the drier climate failed to improve his health, he came back to Texas two years later. He settled in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], living in his later years with his son, [[John Lafayette Camp, Jr.]]. He died there in 1891 and is buried in the Dignowitty Cemetery.<ref name=\"Grave\" />\n\n[[Camp County, Texas]] was named for him after he introduced the Bill in the state Senate that created the county.\n\n==External links==\n*{{Handbook of Texas|id=fca29|name=John Lafayette Camp}}\n*{{Find a Grave|27761101}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"Grave\">{{cite web |title=Col John Lafayette Camp |url=https://www.findagrave.com/m