on 03 Dec 2012</ref>\n* ''[[Botrychium simplex]]'' {{au|E.Hitchc. 1823}} \u2013 least moonwort,<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=200002879 ''B. simplex''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> little grapefern, least grapefern\n* ''[[Botrychium socorrense]]'' {{au|W.H.Wagner 1989}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26616257 ''B. socorrense''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 Isla Socorro moonwort\n* ''[[Botrychium spathulatum]]'' {{au|W.H.Wagner 1990}} \u2013 spatulate moonwort,<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500295 ''B. spathulatum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> spoon-leaved moonwort\n* ''[[Botrychium tunux]]'' {{au|Stensvold & Farrar 2002}}<ref>{{PLANTS|id=BOTU3|taxon=Botrychium tunux|accessdate=27 Dec 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/50270442 ''B. tunux''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 moosewort<ref>[http://www.public.iastate.edu/~herbarium/botrychium/B-tunux.pdf ''B. tunux''] Iowa State Herbarium 03 Jan 2012</ref>\n* ''[[Botrychium \u00d7 watertonense]]'' {{au|W.H.Wagner [hesperium \u00d7 paradoxum]}} \u2013 Waterton grapefern<ref>{{PLANTS|id=BOWA2|taxon=Botrychium \u00d7watertonense|accessdate=27 Dec 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Botrychium yaaxudakeit]]'' {{au|Stensvold & Farrar 2002}}<ref>{{PLANTS|id=BOYA|taxon=Botrychium yaaxudakeit|accessdate=27 Dec 2011}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/50270445 ''B. yaaxudakeit''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 giant moonwort, Yakutat moonwort<ref>[http://www.public.iastate.edu/~herbarium/botrychium/B-yaaxudakeit.pdf ''B. yaaxudakeit''] Iowa State Herbarium 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n\n[[File:Botrychium virginianum.JPG|thumb|right|''Botrychium virginianum'']]\n\n===''Botrychium'' species placed in ''Botrypus''===\n\nThe rattlesnake fern has traditionally been placed in the ''Botrychium'' subgenus '''''Osmundopteris''''', the name of which is based on the species' superficial similarities to the genus ''Osmunda''<ref>Cobb, Farsworth & Lowe, ''Ferns of Northeastern North America'' 2nd edition, p. 247 (2005)</ref> where it was previously placed.\n* ''[[Botrychium virginianum]]'' {{au|(L.) Sw. 1801}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26602189 ''B. virginianum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 Rattlesnake fern,<ref>{{PLANTS|id=BOVI|taxon=B. virginianum|accessdate=27 Dec 2011}}</ref> common grapefern<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500296 ''B. virginianum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref><br>= ''[[Botrypus virginianus]]'' {{au|(L.) Michx. 1803}}\n\n===''Botrychium'' species placed in ''Sceptridium''===\n[[File:Botrychium rugulosum by OpenCage.jpg|thumb|right|''Botrychium rugulosum'']]\nThese species (the evergreen grapeferns) have traditionally been placed in the ''Botrychium'' subgenus '''''Sceptridium''''',a name based on the apparent similarity of their [[sporangia]] to \"little scepters.\"<ref>Cobb, Farsworth & Lowe, ''Ferns of Northeastern North America'' 2nd edition, p. 265 (2005)</ref>\n\n* ''[[Botrychium australe]]'' {{au|R.Br. 1810}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=Dave|title=Demography and conservation of Botrychium australe, a peculiar, sparse mycorrhizal fern|journal=New Zealand Journal of Botany|year=1994|volume=32|issue=4|pages=393\u2013400|doi=10.1080/0028825x.1994.10412925}}</ref> \u2013 Parsley Fern<ref>[http://www.pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Botrychium+australe ''B. australe''] Plants for a Future 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''[[Sceptridium australe]]'' {{au|(R.Br.) Lyon 1905}}<ref>[http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=228864-2 International Plant Names Index (IPNI) 17 Jan 2011]</ref>\n\n* ''[[Botrychium biforme]]'' {{au|Colenso 1886}}<ref>[http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=17060960-1 ''B. biforme''] International Plant Names Index (IPNI) 02 Jan 2012</ref> \u2013 Fine-leaved parsley fern\n:= ''[[Sceptridium biforme]]'' {{au|(Colenso) Lyon 1905}}<ref>[http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=17220050-1 ''S. biforme''] International Plant Names Index (IPNI) 02 Jan 2012</ref>\n\n* ''[[Botrychium biternatum]]'' {{au|(Savigny) Underw. 1896}} \u2013 Sparse-lobed grapefern, Southern grapefern<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500272 ''B. biternatum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''Osmunda biternata'' {{au|Savigny 1798}}\n:= ''[[Sceptridium biternatum]]'' {{au|(Savigny) Lyon 1905}}\n\n* ''[[Botrychium dissectum]]'' {{au|Sprengel 1804}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Montgomery|first=James D.|title=Survivorship and Predation Changes in Five Populations of Botrychium dissectum in Eastern Pennsylvania|journal=American Fern Journal|year=1990|volume=80|issue=4|series=4|pages=173\u2013182|doi=10.2307/1547206|jstor=1547206}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26602173 ''B. dissectum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 Dissected grapefern<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=200002874 ''B. dissectum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> or Cut-leaved grape-fern<ref name=mich>[http://michiganflora.net/genus.aspx?id=Sceptridium] MICHIGAN FLORA ONLINE. A. A. Reznicek, E. G. Voss, & B. S. Walters. February 2011. University of Michigan. Web. January 16, 2012</ref>\n:= ''Botrychium obliquum'' {{au|Muhl. 1810}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26604109?tab=acceptednames ''B. obliquum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 16 Jan 2012</ref>\n:= ''[[Sceptridium dissectum]]'' {{au|(Spreng.) Lyon 1905}}\n\n* ''[[Botrychium jenmanii]]'' {{au|Underw. 1900}} \u2013 Alabama grapefern<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500279 ''B. jenmanii''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26602175 ''B. jenmanii''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''[[Sceptridium jenmanii]]'' {{au|(Underw.) Lyon 1905}}\n:= ''Botrychium alabamense'' {{au|Maxon 1906}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26602175?tab=synonyms ''B. alabamense''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''Sceptridium alabamense'' {{au|(Maxon) Holub. 1973}}\n\n* ''[[Botrychium multifidum]]'' {{au|(S.G. Gmel.) Rupr. 1859}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mesipuu|first=Meeli|author2=R. P. Shefferson|author3=T. Kull|title=Weather and herbivores influence fertility in the endangered fern Botrychium multifidum (S.G. Gmel.) Rupr|journal=Plant Ecology|year=2009|volume=203|pages=23\u201331|doi=10.1007/s11258-008-9501-3}}</ref><ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26610816 ''B. multifidum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 Leather grapefern<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500286 ''B. multifidum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref><ref>{{PLANTS|id=BOMU|taxon=Botrychium multifidum}}</ref><ref>[http://www.uwgb.edu/biodiversity/herbarium/pteridophytes/botmul01.htm ''B. multifidum''] University of Wisconsin, Cofrin Center for Biodiversity, Ferns and Fern Allies of Wisconsin. 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''Osmunda multifida'' {{au|S.G. Gmel. 1768}}\n:= ''Botrychium silaifolium'' {{au|C.Presl 1825}}\n:= ''Botrychium matricariae'' {{au|(Schrank) Spreng. 1827}}<ref>[http://wisplants.uwsp.edu/scripts/SearchResults.asp?Genus=Botrychium ''Botrychium''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317084213/http://wisplants.uwsp.edu/scripts/SearchResults.asp?Genus=Botrychium |date=2013-03-17 }} Robert W. Freckmann Herbarium,\nUniversity of Wisconsin - Stevens Point 02 Jan 2012</ref>\n:= ''[[Sceptridium multifidum]]'' {{au|(S.G.Gmel.) Nishida ex Tagawa 1958}}\n\n* ''[[Botrychium oneidense]]'' {{au|(Gilbert) House 1905}} \u2013 Blunt-lobed grapefern<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500287 ''B. oneidense''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''[[Sceptridium oneidense]]'' {{au|(Gilbert) Holub 1998}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26602184 ''Botrychium oneidense''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 16 Jan 2012</ref>\n\n* ''[[Botrychium rugulosum]]'' {{au|W.H.Wagner 1982}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26604473 ''B. rugulosum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 26 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 St. Lawrence grape fern, Rugulose grape fern, Ternate grape fern<ref name=botrug>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100610054315/http://wisplants.uwsp.edu/scripts/Detail.asp?Spcode=BOTRUG ''B. rugulosum''] Robert W. Freckmann Herbarium, University of Wisconsin - Stevens Point 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''Botrychium ternatum'' {{au|auct. non (Thunb.) Sw. 1801}}\n:= ''[[Sceptridium rugulosum]]'' {{au|(W.H.Wagner) Skoda & Holub 1996}}\n\n* ''[[Botrychium schaffneri]]'' {{au|Underw. 1903}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26606088 ''B. schaffneri''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 04 Jan 2012</ref> \u2013\n* ''[[Botrychium subbifoliatum]]'' {{au|Brack. 1854}}<ref>[http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=17061550-1 ''B. subbifoliatum''] International Plant Names Index 27 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 Island grapefern<ref>[https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=17193 ''B. subbifoliatum''] ITIS taxonomy  26 Dec 2011</ref><ref>{{PLANTS|id=SCSU13|taxon=Sceptridium subbifoliatum|accessdate=26 Dec 2011}}</ref><br> = ''[[Sceptridium subbifoliatum]]'' {{au|(Brack.) Lyon 1905}}\n* ''[[Botrychium underwoodianum]]'' {{au|Maxon 1905}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26608302 ''B. underwoodianum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n:= ''Botrychium ternatum'' {{au|(Thunb.) Sw. 1801}}\n:= ''[[Sceptridium underwoodianum]]'' {{au|(Maxon) Lyon 1905}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26619756 ''S. underwoodianum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\n\nMoonworts can be found in many environments, including prairies, forests, and mountains.  While some Botrychium species are quite rare, conservation efforts can be difficult.  Determining the rarity of a species is complicated by the plants\u2019 small leaves, which stand only 2-10 centimeters above the soil.<ref name=\"Johnson-Groh2002\">{{cite journal | last1 = Johnson-Groh | first1 = C. L. | last2 = Lee | first2 = J. | year = 2002 | title = Phenology and demography of two species of Botrychium (Ophioglassaceae) | url = | journal = American Journal of Botany | volume = 89 | issue = 10| pages = 1624\u20131633 }}</ref>  Even more of a challenge in obtaining an accurate population count is the genus\u2019s largely subterranean life cycle.  The vast majority of any one population of moonworts actually exists below ground in banks consisting of several types of propagules.  One type of propagule is the ungerminated spores, which must percolate through the soil beyond the reach of light in order to germinate.  This presumably increases the probability that the spore will be in range of a mycorrhizal symbiont before it produces the tiny, roughly heart-shaped gametophyte, which also exists entirely below ground.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Whittier | first1 = D | year = 1973 | title = The effect of light and other factors on spore germination in Botrychium dissectum | url = | journal = Can J Bot | volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 1791\u20131794 }}</ref>  Finally, some species produce gemmae, a form of asexual propagation achieved by budding of the root.<ref name=\"Johnson-Groh2002\" />\n\nJuvenile and dormant [[sporophyte]]s can also be hidden in the soil for long periods of time.  Mature sporophytes do not necessarily produce a leaf annually; they can remain viable underground for up to 10 years without putting up a photosynthetic component.  This feat is made possible by their dependence on symbiotic partnership with AM fungi of the genus Glomus, which supply most fixed carbon for growth and reproduction.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Winther | first1 = J | last2 = Friedman | first2 = W | year = 2007 | title = Arbuscular mycorrhizal symbionts in Botrychium (Ophioglossaceae) | url = | journal = Am J Bot | volume = 94 | issue = 7| pages = 1248\u20131255 }}</ref>\n\nThis mycorrhizal dependence has also made lab cultivation of moonworts difficult.  Thus far, only germination of the gametophyte has been successful.\n\n<!-- \nThe only British species is the ''Botrychium lunaria'' ('moonwort'), a little plant pretty frequent in dry mountain pastures.  About a dozen species occur in the United States, ''Botrychium lunaria'' ranges from [[Colorado]] to [[New England]], [[Lake Superior]], and sparingly northward.  ''Botrychium simplex'', a rare species, with small fronds, is found from [[California]] and [[Yellowstone National Park|Yellowstone Park]] to Lake Superior and eastward.  ''Botrychium lanceolatum'' ranges from Colorado to Lake Superior, [[Ohio]], [[New Jersey]], and New England.  ''Botrychium lunarioides'' is found from [[Massachusetts]] to [[Florida]] in dry, rich woods and shady pastures.  ''Botrychium ternatum'' occurs throughout [[North America]].\n[this is pretty useless information, as it deals with Botrychium sensu lato, and only from a USUK perspective.]\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|24em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://plants.usda.gov/core/profile?symbol=BOTRY  USDA Plants Profile for ''Botrychium'' (grapeferns)]\n* [http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=104332 Efloras.org: Flora of North America, treatment of genus ''Botrychium'']\n*[https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=17170#null  ITIS.gov: List of ''Botrychium'' species] \u2014 ''with species links''.\n{{Commons category|position=left|Botrychium}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1353804}}\n\n[[Category:Ophioglossaceae]]\n[[Category:Fern genera]]\n[[Category:Ferns of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Ferns of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Genus of ferns in the family Ophioglossaceae}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| name = Moonwort\n| image = Botrychium-4.jpg\n| image_caption = ''Botrychium lunaria''\n| taxon = Botrychium\n| authority = [[Olof Swartz|Sw.]]\n| subdivision_ranks = [[Species]]\n| subdivision = Several, see text\n}}\n\n'''''Botrychium''''' is a genus of [[fern]]s, seedless [[vascular plant]]s in the family [[Ophioglossaceae]].<ref name=\"Christenhusz_2011b\">{{cite journal | last1 = Christenhusz | first1 = Maarten J. M. | last2 = Zhang| first2 = Xian-Chun | last3 = Schneider | first3 = Harald | year = 2011 | title = A linear sequence of extant families and genera of lycophytes and ferns | url = http://www.mapress.com/phytotaxa/content/2011/f/pt00019p054.pdf | format = PDF | journal = Phytotaxa | volume = 19 | pages = 7\u201354 }}</ref> ''Botrychium'' species are known as '''moonworts'''. They are small, with fleshy [[root]]s, and reproduce by [[spore]]s shed into the air. One part of the leaf, the trophophore, is sterile and fernlike; the other, the [[sporophore]], is fertile and carries the clusters of sporangia or spore cases.  Some species only occasionally emerge above ground and gain most of their nourishment from an association with mycorrhizal [[fungus|fungi]].\n\n<!-- [[Image:BotrychiumLunaria1.jpg|left|frame|Moonwort (''Botrychium lunaria'')]] [messes up layout real bad. Not in Commons, so it is left here for species article] -->\nThe circumscription of ''Botrychium'' is disputed between different authors; some botanists include the genera ''[[Botrypus]]'' and ''[[Sceptridium]]'' within ''Botrychium'', while others treat them as distinct. The latter treatment is provisionally followed here.\n\n==Selected species==\n\n===Botrychium s.s., the moonworts===\n\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium acuminatum]]|[[W.H.Wagner]] 1990}} \u2013 pointed moonwort<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500271 ''B. acuminatum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium alaskense]]|W.H.Wagner & J.R.Grant 2002}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/100367914 ''B. alaskense''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 27 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 Alaska moonwort<ref>[http://www.public.iastate.edu/~herbarium/botrychium/B-alaskense.pdf ''B. alaskense''] Iowa State Herbarium 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium ascendens]]|W.H.Wagner 1986}} \u2013 upswept moonwort,<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500270 ''B. ascendens''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> triangle-lobed moonwort, upward-lobed moonwort\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium boreale]]|J.Milde 1857}} \u2013 northern moonwort<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500273 ''B. boreale''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium chamaeconium]]|Bitter & Hieron. 1900}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26605833 ''B. chamaeconium''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 02 Jan 2012</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium campestre]]|W.H.Wagner & Farrar}} \u2013 prairie moonwort,<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500274 ''B. campestre''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> prairie dunewort, Iowa moonwort<ref>[http://wisplants.uwsp.edu/scripts/SearchResults.asp?Genus=Botrychium ''B. campestre''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317084213/http://wisplants.uwsp.edu/scripts/SearchResults.asp?Genus=Botrychium |date=2013-03-17 }} Robert W. Freckmann Herbarium\nUniversity of Wisconsin - Stevens Point 27 Dec 2011</ref>\n\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium crenulatum]]|W.H.Wagner 1981}} \u2013 dainty moonwort,<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500275 ''B. crenulatum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> crenulate moonwort\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium daucifolium]]|Wall. ex Hook. & Grev. 1830}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26609745 ''B. daucifolium''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 27 Dec 2011</ref> \u2013 thin-leaved moonwort<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=101&taxon_id=242308863 ''B. daucifolium''] Taiwan Plant Names, www.eFlora.org  27 Dec 2011</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium echo]]|W.H.Wagner 1983}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26604469 ''B. echo''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 03 Jan 2012</ref> \u2013 reflected grapfern<ref>[http://www.fs.fed.us/r2/projects/scp/assessments/botrychiumecho.pdf ''B. echo''] USDA Forest Service,Rocky Mountain Region, Species Conservation Project July 22, 2004</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium gallicomontanum]]|Farrar & Johnson-Groh 1991}}<ref name=\"Johnson-Groh2002\" /> \u2013 Frenchman's Bluff moonwort<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500277 ''B. gallicomontanum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium hesperium]]|Maxon & R.T.Clausen) W.H.Wagner & Lellinger 1981}} \u2013 western moonwort<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=233500278 ''B. hesperium''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium japonicum]]|(Prantl) Underw. 1898}}<ref>[http://www.tropicos.org/Name/26610083 ''B. japonicum''] Tropicos.org. Missouri Botanical Garden. 02 Jan 2012</ref>\n* {{tx|[[Botrychium lanceolatum]]|(Gmel) \u00c5ngstr. 1854}} \u2013 triangle moonwort,<ref>[http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=1&taxon_id=200002875 ''B. lanceolatum''] Flora of North America, www.eFloras.org 26 Dec 2011</ref> triangle grapefern, lance-leaved grapefern\n* ''[[Botrychium lineare]]'' {{au|W.H.Wagner 1994}} \u2013 skinny moonwort,<ref>[http://www1.dnr.wa.gov/nhp/refdesk/fguide/pdf/botlin.pdf ''B. lineare''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426072518/http://www1.dnr.wa.gov/nhp/refdesk/fguide/pdf/botlin.pdf |date=April 